description:
Given the following:

- We have an epic `Aliquam`
- The `Aliquam` epic contains a sub-epic `Subepic`
- We have an issue `new issue` which is assigned to the `Subepic` sub-epic

Then on the issues Haml page, we can filter the issues by the `Aliquam` epic with the URL param `include_subepics=✓` and the `new issue` issue will be in the results because the results contain any issues that are part of the `Aliquam` epic or any of its sub-epics.

![Screenshot_2021-08-12_at_3.29.27_pm](/uploads/37d4bccc5f2897ad40609ab29d678bdb/Screenshot_2021-08-12_at_3.29.27_pm.png)

However, in the GraphQL API we are currently not able to get a list of issues that are part of the `Aliquam` epic or any of its sub-epics. This is required for the Vue issues page refactor.

```js
// can filter by epic, but cannot filter by epic and its sub-epics
{
  project(fullPath: "h5bp/html5-boilerplate") {
    issues(epicId: "32") {
      nodes {
        id
        title
      }
    }
  }
}
```

## Proposal

We could add a new parameter to the `IssueConnection` type so that we can filter issues by an epic including its sub-epics.

The new parameter could be named:

- `includeSubEpics`, to match the URL param used on the Haml issues page
- `includeChildren`, because in the epics documentation we do not refer to them as sub-epics but as children. As the naming is more generic, it could be used with other params but maybe this doesn't make sense

```js
// proposal to filter by epic and its sub-epics
{
  project(fullPath: "h5bp/html5-boilerplate") {
    issues(epicId: "32", includeSubEpics: true) {
      nodes {
        id
        title
      }
    }
  }
}
```

## Acceptance criteria

- For project issues in GraphQL, the user can provide an epic ID (with additional arguments) and get a list of issues that are assigned to that epic or any of its sub-epics

Seeing how this [pull request](https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch-py/pull/1623) was merged into the official `elasticsearch-py` client library raises some concerns about GitLab's future ES version compatability. We need to make sure that we keep the broadest possible compatibility when updating ES client libraries. We might need to change our testing pipelines, for example, by running the official distribution by default for every commit and a non-official distribution nightly (or on demand).

@ebanks WDYT about these risks? In your opinion, is it worth investing into additional testing pipeline?

cc @terrichu @JohnMcGuire @changzhengliu
